Western Cape premier Alan Winde has reported 599 confirmed cases of Covid-19 coronavirus infections in the province as of midnight on 12 April. Khayelitsha, the largest township in the Western Cape, with a population of around 400,000 people, has 14 confirmed cases. “Currently, 24 people who have tested positive for Covid-19 infection are being treated in hospital, with 11 of these receiving care in ICU. “We also recorded the seventh death in the province yesterday- a 61-year old male. We extend our thoughts and condolences to his family and loved ones at this time,” said Winde. “We are encouraged that the growth in the number of new cases in many of our non-metro areas has been minimal,” he said. <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-389179" src="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/WesternCape.jpg" alt="" width="960" height="530" srcset="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/WesternCape.jpg 960w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/WesternCape-300x166.jpg 300w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/WesternCape-768x424.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px" /> Sub Districts Non-Metro: Garden Route Bitou – 5
